Most commercial shotguns have a bore diameter greater than 1 â„2 inch, but are exempt due to their "sporting purpose"; however, both the Street Sweeper and USAS-12 shotguns, designed for military or police use, were reclassified as DDs when the ATF determined they were combat shotguns not "generally recognized as particularly suitable for sporting purposes". Devices which are not intended or not likely to be used as a weapon are also exempt. Examples of nonweapon large bore firearms include: Line-throwing devices for marine rescue, such as lyle guns and rockets for breeches buoys. Flare launchers are normally exempt as they are signalling devices, not weapons; however, possession of a flare launcher and anti-personnel ammunition for it puts it in the DD category as it is then considered to be a weapon. The legal term silencer, also known as a "suppressor", is defined as "any device for silencing, muffling, or diminishing the report of a portable firearm, including any combination of parts ... intended for use in assembling or fabricating a firearm silencer."[18] "Any other weapon" is a "catch-all" category. An AOW is defined as "any weapon or device capable of being concealed on the person from which a shot can be discharged through the energy of an explosive," other than a handgun with a rifled barrel.[3] This umbrella definition includes many improvised firearms ("zip guns") and disguised firearms. Examples include wallet guns, cane guns, knife guns and pen guns. Why Bangladeshi hate India??? Because:- 1. Interference in Internal Politics: India is perceived to have interfered in Bangladesh's internal politics, particularly during the elections of 2008, 2014, 2018, and 2024. Former Indian President Pranab Mukherjee mentioned in his book "The Coalition Years" about India's involvement in the 2008 Bangladesh elections. Additionally, in the 2014 elections, Indian diplomat Sushma Swaraj allegedly pressured Jatiya Party leader Ershad to participate, which he later acknowledged, lending legitimacy to the elections. 2. Border Killings: Between 2001 and 2010, approximately 1,000 Bangladeshi civilians were killed by the Indian Border Security Force (BSF) along the India-Bangladesh border.( source wikipedia)  From 2011 to 2020, 334 Bangladeshis were killed by the BSF.(source- Human rights watch) 3. Water Disputes: India has constructed dams on transboundary rivers, affecting the water flow into Bangladesh. This includes blocking water from 54 rivers, which has significant impacts on Bangladesh's water resources. 4. Media Portrayal: Indian media, including dramas and movies, often portray Bangladesh negatively, spreading false propaganda and fostering hatred. 5. Political Remarks: Indian politicians, especially from the BJP, have made derogatory comments about Bangladesh, which fuels negative sentiments.

In India, communal riots related to Muslim deaths occurred in various regions during different years. Here are some notable instances: - In 1961, in Aligarh - In 1962, in Jabalpur, Madhya Pradesh - In 1964, in Vibhavari, Maharashtra - In 1967, in Ranchi, Bihar - In 1969, in Ahmedabad, Gujarat - In 1970, in Vidyavihar, Jalgaon, and Malad, Maharashtra - In 1971, in Bihar - From 1978 to 1980, in Jamshedpur (Bihar) and Uttar Pradesh - In 1980, in Muradabad, Uttar Pradesh - In 1981, in Minakshipuram (Aligarh) and Bihar Sharif - In 1982, in Meerut, Uttar Pradesh - In 1983, in Assam - In 1983, in Bhagalpur, Bihar - In 1986, in Noida, Uttar Pradesh - In 1987, in Meerut, Uttar Pradesh - In 1989, in Bhagalpur, Bihar - From 1990 to 1991, in Aligarh - From 1992 to 1993, in Mumbai, Surat, Ahmedabad, Kanpur, and Delhi - In 1997, in Tamil Nadu - In 2000, in Ahmedabad - In 2001, in Kanpur and Maligaon - In 2002, in Gujarat - In 2003, there were a total of 711 communal riots related to Muslim deaths - In 2004, there were 677 such riots - In 2005, there were 779 such riots - In 2006, there were 698 such riots - In 1987, the Hashimpura massacre occurred - In 1992, the Bombay riots took place - In 1983, the Nellie massacre happened - In 2013, the Muzaffarnagar violence occurred - In 2002, the Gujarat riots took place - In 2020, the Delhi riots happened - In 2012, the Kokrajhar killings occurred - In 2014, the Ballabgarh lynching took place According to the Ministry of Home Affairs in India, between 1954 and 1992, there were approximately 13,356 major communal riots related to anti-Muslim sentiments.
